		<pubDate>Thu, 17 Sep 2015 04:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/?p=9690#comment-16434</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[It turns not quite everyone&#039;s fret hand physiology is the same.  I don&#039;t have the tendon in the elbow that keeps the ulnar nerve in place so at a certain bend it jumps out and rolls over the bone.  It kind of saws at the nerve really.  Didn&#039;t bother me years ago when I was gigging but since then I&#039;ve been in a car wreck where my thumb got scrumpled (bent completely back) and a certain antibiotic I was on gave me severe tendinitis and did some nerve damage.  Now my left arm doesn&#039;t really listen to my brain that well but I&#039;m trying to work through it.  There were a couple of things I wanted to mention. 

1. many months after my thumb was scrumpled I attempted playing.  Athletic tape to support it was necessary but would stick to the neck.  A partial glove allowed free movement.  Without knowing of your condition this caused me to click on the first video of yours I came across.

2. ring to pinky hammers my thumb creeps out.  I never noticed this before so thank you!  It&#039;s my worst finger combo, being cognizant of thumb position will help.]]></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>It turns not quite everyone&#8217;s fret hand physiology is the same.  I don&#8217;t have the tendon in the elbow that keeps the ulnar nerve in place so at a certain bend it jumps out and rolls over the bone.  It kind of saws at the nerve really.  Didn&#8217;t bother me years ago when I was gigging but since then I&#8217;ve been in a car wreck where my thumb got scrumpled (bent completely back) and a certain antibiotic I was on gave me severe tendinitis and did some nerve damage.  Now my left arm doesn&#8217;t really listen to my brain that well but I&#8217;m trying to work through it.  There were a couple of things I wanted to mention. </p>
<p>1. many months after my thumb was scrumpled I attempted playing.  Athletic tape to support it was necessary but would stick to the neck.  A partial glove allowed free movement.  Without knowing of your condition this caused me to click on the first video of yours I came across.</p>
<p>2. ring to pinky hammers my thumb creeps out.  I never noticed this before so thank you!  It&#8217;s my worst finger combo, being cognizant of thumb position will help.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
